`ppi_document_for_file` creates a PPI document is such a way:

```
my $encoded_content = $file->encoded_content;
...
my $document = PPI::Document->new(\$encoded_content);
```

Since PPI document is created from string, it does not know its filename. It makes creating error messages hardly possible.

[I have requested PP to accept `filename` argument](https://github.com/adamkennedy/PPI/issues/180), so `Dist::Zilla` can pass filename to the constructor:

```
my $document = PPI::Document->new(\$encoded_content, filename => $file->name);
```

Meanwhile, `Dist::Zilla` can pass filename through file content by using `#line` directive:

```
$encoded_content = "#line 1 " . $file->name . "\n" . $encoded_content;
my $document = PPI::Document->new(\$encoded_content);
```

Later, if `PPI` implements `filename` argument, `Dist::Zilla` can utilize it, keeping `#line` directive as a backup:

```
if ( PPI::Document->VERSION() >= XXX ) {
    $document = PPI::Document->new(\$encoded_content, filename => $file->name);
} else {
    $encoded_content = "#line 1 " . $file->name . "\n" . $encoded_content;
    $document = PPI::Document->new(\$encoded_content);
};
```

In my understanding:

``` perl
use 5.010;
```

In `Makefile.PL` is a clear indicator that `5.010` is the minimum for configuration. 

However, that value is computed from the maximum value of ( configure/runtime/test/build ) phases, and so the `use`'d version can be subsequently much higher than the value in `configure.requires`.

Subsequently, this implies that by Makefile.PL aggregating `perl` version requirements from other phases and taking the maximum value, `Makefile.PL` raises the configure requirement to the maximum version.

However, after it raises this maximum version, it doesn't inject that maximum back into `$zilla->prereqs`, and so no other plugins are aware that `Makefile.PL` has raised the configure requirements.

So `META.json` and `META.yml` continue with the _lower_ configure requirement value, which can be evidentially demonstrated to be false:
1. Satisfy `configure.requires` and **only** configure.requires
2. 5.006 satisfies `configure.requires => {perl => 5.006}`
3. execute perl Makefile.PL
4. Makefile.PL dies.

To demonstrate this:

``` perl
use strict;
use warnings;

use Test::More;

# FILENAME: annoying.t
# CREATED: 26/09/15 16:45:16 by Kent Fredric (kentnl) <kentfredric@gmail.com>
# ABSTRACT: An annoying issue

use Test::DZil qw( Builder simple_ini );
use Path::Tiny qw( path );

my %files;

$files{ path( 'source', 'dist.ini' ) } = simple_ini(
    ['Prereqs' => 'ConfigureRequires' => {
        perl => '5.006',
    }],
    ['Prereqs' => 'RuntimeRequires' => {
        perl => '5.010',
    }],
    ['MetaYAML'], ['MetaJSON'],
    ['MakeMaker'],
);

my $tzil = Builder->from_config( { dist_root => 'not-exists', },
    { add_files => \%files } );

$tzil->build;

my ($makefile) = grep { $_->name eq 'Makefile.PL' } @{ $tzil->files };
my ($metayml)  = grep { $_->name eq 'META.yml' } @{ $tzil->files };

like $makefile->content, qr/use 5\.010;/, 'Makefile.PL <use>\'s 5.010';
like $makefile->content, qr/MIN_PERL_VERSION" => "5\.010"/,
  'Makefile.PL min_perl is 5.010';

my $configure_requires =
  $tzil->prereqs->requirements_for( 'configure', 'requires' )->as_string_hash;
isnt( $configure_requires->{perl},
    '5.006', 'Configure requires sure as fuck needs 5.010' );

use Term::ANSIColor qw( colored );
diag colored("Makefile.PL: >>>" , 'bright_green' );
diag colored($makefile->content, 'green' );

diag colored("META.yml: >>>", 'bright_red');
diag colored($metayml->content, 'red' );

done_testing;
```

The simplest thing that could possibly work is of course just replicating that behaviour in the `register_prereqs` phase, but that is of course incredibly order-dependent.

``` perl
sub register_prereqs {
  my ($self) = @_;

  $self->zilla->register_prereqs(
    { phase => 'configure' },
    'ExtUtils::MakeMaker' => $self->eumm_version || 0,
  );
  my $perl_prereq = $self->_pl_req;
  $self->zilla->register_prereqs(
    { phase => 'configure' },
    perl => $perl_prereq
  ) if $perl_prereq;
```

( where _pl_req is returns [this logic](https://metacpan.org/source/RJBS/Dist-Zilla-5.039/lib/Dist/Zilla/Plugin/MakeMaker.pm#L187-193) )

And that seems to do the trick.

